Introduction¶

This project is an investigation on the movie data from TMDb. The aim is to investigate the dataset, carry out an analysis, and make inferences from the analysis done.

The original dataset has 21 columns [or variables] & 10866 rows [or entries]. The columns are:

  • id - The movie id.
  • imdb_id - movie id on IMDb.
  • popularity - This represents the popularity.
  • budget - This represents the budget that was used to produced a movie in dollars.
  • revenue - This represents the revenue that made from a movie in dollars.
  • original_title - This represents the title of a movie.
  • cast - This represents the cast of actors/actresses that starred in a movie.
  • homepage - This represents the website of the movie.
  • director - This represents the director that directed the movie
  • tagline - This represents the tagline associated to a movie.
  • keywords - This represents the keywords associated to a movie.
  • overview - This represents the synopsis of a movie.
  • runtime - This represents the runtime of the movie.
  • genres - This represents the genre of the movie.
  • production_companies - This represents companies that produced the movies.
  • release_date - This represents the date the movies was released.
  • vote_count - This represents the number of the audience that rated a movie.
  • vote_average - This represents the average rating of a movie.
  • release_year - This represents the year a movie was released.
  • budget_adj - This isn't very clear, but it is similar to the 'budget' column.
  • revenue_adj - This isn't very clear, but it is similar to the 'revenue' column.

An intial eight (8) research questions will be asked to test the relationship between the different variables. These questions are:

  1. Which movies are the most popular?
  2. Which directors are the most popular?
  3. Which directors feature most in the data?
  4. Which movies made the most revenue?
  5. Which movies made the most profit?
  6. Which year produced the most movies?
  7. Does runtime affect ratings?
  8. Does runtime affect popularity?

Data Cleaning¶

What needs to be done to clean:

  • Drop the "budget_adj" & "revenue_adj" columns
  • Drop the following columns: 'keywords', 'tagline', 'imdb_id', 'overview' & 'homepage'
  • Drop rows in the 'budget' & revenue' columns that have Zero Values.

In [13]:
# Drop the "budget_adj" & "revenue_adj" columns
df_movie = df_movie.drop(['budget_adj', 'revenue_adj'], axis=1)

The bar chart above provides information on the top 20 directors that were featured on the dataset. In this chart, we are able to see the directors that have directed the most movies in the dataset.

OBSERVATION THREE¶

Steven Spielberg, Clint Eastwood, & Ridley Scott have directed the most movies in the period under review.

On further review outside the dataset, we see that the age and longevity of Steven Spielberg, Clint Eastwood, & Ridley Scott have played a role in volume of movies they have directed.

  • Steven Spielberg is 75 yrs old and active since 1959.
  • Clint Eastwood is 91 yrs old and active since 1963.
  • Ridley Scott is 84 yrs old and active since 1962.

    • Despite having more than one movie in the Top 20 most popular movies, Christopher Nolan, & Peter Jackson do not appear on the Top 20 list of directors to have directed the most movies in the period under review.

    We also see that none of the movies of the directors that featured most in the dataset made the top 20 most popular movies.

    Conclusions¶

    At the start of this analysis, eight (8) questions were asked to test the relationship between the different variables. These questions were:

    1. Which movies are the most popular?
    2. Which directors are the most popular?
    3. Which directors feature most in the data?
    4. Which movies made the most revenue?
    5. Which movies made the most profit?
    6. Which year produced the most movies?
    7. Does runtime affect ratings?
    8. Does runtime affect popularity?

    At the end of the analysis, some observations were made. These observations are highlighted below:

    OBSERVATION ONE:¶

    The Top 10 most popular movies are:

    1. Jurassic World
    2. Mad Max: Fury Road
    3. Interstellar
    4. Guardians of the Galaxy
    5. Insurgent
    6. Captain America: The Winter Soldier
    7. Star Wars
    8. John Wick
    9. Star Wars: The Force Awakens
    10. The Hunger Games: Mockingjay - Part 1

    A bar chart further revealed that the Top 3 movies ['Jurassic World', 'Mad Max: Fury Road', & 'Interstellar'] were evidently clear of the rest in popularity. See image below:

    OBSERVATION TWO:¶

    The names of the directors that directed the Top 10 most popular movies are:

    1. JColin Trevorrow
    2. George Miller
    3. Christopher Nolan
    4. James Gunn
    5. Robert Schwentke
    6. Joe Russo|Anthony Russo
    7. George Lucas
    8. Chad Stahelski|David Leitch
    9. J.J. Abrams
    10. Francis Lawrence

    Christopher Nolan & Peter Jackson are the only directors that directed more than one movie on the list of the Top 20 most popular movies. This provides an indication on their quality as one of the best directors to have ever graced the movie scene.

    OBSERVATION THREE:¶

    Steven Spielberg, Clint Eastwood, & Ridley Scott have directed the most movies in the period under review. See image below:

    On further review outside the dataset, we see that the age and longevity of Steven Spielberg, Clint Eastwood, & Ridley Scott have played a role in volume of movies they have directed.

  • Steven Spielberg is 75 yrs old and active since 1959.
  • Clint Eastwood is 91 yrs old and active since 1963.
  • Ridley Scott is 84 yrs old and active since 1962.

    • Despite having more than one movie in the Top 20 most popular movies, Christopher Nolan, & Peter Jackson do not appear on the Top 20 list of directors to have directed the most movies in the period under review.

    None of the movies of the directors that featured most in the dataset made the top 20 most popular movies.

    OBSERVATION FOUR:¶

    Avatar outstandingly performed better than every other movie in terms of revenue generated. See image below:

    OBSERVATION EIGHT:¶

    We see that the average runtime for the highly popular movies is 37.2 minutes longer than the average runtime for the lowly popular movies.

    This suggests that the length of movie does not necessarily influence the popularity of a movie.

    Limitations:¶

    The analysis carried out here is not exhaustive. A few limitations exist within this analysis and there are further questions that can be asked for further exploration.

    An example of the few limitations is the fact that I limited top performance of certain variables to a list of Top 20 or Top 10. This might not tell the full story of what it is really going on. Also, during the cleaning of the orginal dataset, I had to drop up to 50% of the rows because they had zero values in the 'budget' & 'revenue' columns. This action might have affected other variables like 'director', 'original_title', & 'release_year'

    Despite the limitations, further questions that can be asked for further exploration are:

  • What genre of movies are the most popular?
  • What genre of movies are highly rated?
  • Are the quality of movies produced getting better as the years go by?
  • Which year did movie producers enjoy the most profit?
  • Is there a link between a movie runtime & the revenue made from the movie?
